# Overview

Use the `batchPromises` helper instead of naive `for...of` loops or `Promise.all` when performing large-scale async operations. This prevents memory spikes and rate-limit errors by processing items in controlled concurrency windows.

## When to Apply

- Iterating over an array and calling an async function per item (API calls, DB writes, file I/O, etc.)
- Any `Promise.all(items.map(...))` that could run unbounded in parallel
- `for...of` loops with `await` inside that process more than a handful of items

## Usage
```ts
import { batchPromises } from '../utils/batch.js';

// ✅ Preferred
const results = await batchPromises(items, (item) => processItem(item));

// ❌ Avoid — unbounded parallelism
const results = await Promise.all(items.map((item) => processItem(item)));

// ❌ Avoid — fully serial, slow
const results = [];
for (const item of items) {
  results.push(await processItem(item));
}
```